# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: germplasm-resources-information-network
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] Beltsville is adjacent to the Montgomery County – Prince George's County line.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] It is approximately 7 miles (11 km) northeast of the Maryland border with Washington.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] According to the United States Census Bureau, Beltsville has a total area of 7.2 square miles (18.6 km2), of which 7.1 square miles (18.5 km2) is land and 0.04 square miles (0.1 km2), or 0.38%, is water.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] The climate in this area is characterized by hot, humid summers (up to 30.6°C or 87.1°F) and generally mild to cool winters (as low as -3.7°C or 25.3°F).
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] According to the Köppen Climate Classification system, Beltsville has a humid subtropical climate, abbreviated "Cfa" on climate maps.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] As of the 2020 census, Beltsville had a population of 20,133.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] 22.2% of residents were under the age of 18 and 20.0% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] For every 100 females there were 92.8 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 89.2 males age 18 and over.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] 99.9% of residents lived in urban areas, while 0.1% lived in rural areas.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] There were 6,718 households in Beltsville, of which 33.3% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] Of all households, 41.9% were married-couple households, 19.2% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 33.7% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] About 29.3% of all households were made up of individuals and 19.2% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] There were 7,105 housing units, of which 5.4% were vacant.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] The homeowner vacancy rate was 1.3% and the rental vacancy rate was 6.4%.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] As of the census of 2000, there were 15,690 people, 5,690 households, and 3,823 families residing in Beltsville.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] The population density was 2,366.9 inhabitants per square mile (913.9/km2).
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] There were 5,865 housing units at an average density of 884.8 per square mile (341.6/km2).
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] The racial makeup of Beltsville was 48.20% White, 31.96% African American, 0.26% Native American, 10.75% Asian, 0.10% Pacific Islander, 5.42% from other races, and 3.31% from two or more races.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] Hispanic or Latino of any race were 9.84% of the population.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] There were 5,690 households, out of which 32.4% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 49.0% were married couples living together, 13.5% had a female householder with no husband present, and 32.8% were non-families.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] 23.0% of all households were made up of individuals, and 5.1% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] The average household size was 2.74 and the average family size was 3.27.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] In Beltsville the population was spread out, with 23.6% under the age of 18, 10.3% from 18 to 24, 34.5% from 25 to 44, 22.6% from 45 to 64, and 8.9% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] For every 100 females, there were 94.5 males.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 91.8 males.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] The median income for a household in Beltsville was $57,722, and the median income for a family was $66,087.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] Males had a median income of $40,914 with $35,645 for females.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] The per capita income for the CDP was $24,679.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] About 5.5% of families and 7.2% of the population were below the poverty line, including 5.4% of those under age 18 and 7.2% of those age 65 or over.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] Beltsville's history dates back to 1649, when the land was part of an 80,000-acre (324 km2) land grant given to Richard Snowden I by Lord Baltimore of England.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] Snowden and his family were planters who established large plantations on which they built comfortable manor homes.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] Soon after, other settlers moved into the area, but they were farmers who could only afford a few acres of land and whose families lived in small cabins.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] The principal crop was tobacco, most of which was shipped to England.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] Because of the fertile soil and desirable growing conditions, the crops prospered.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] Industry came to Beltsville in the early 18th century when iron ore was discovered in the area.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] The Muirkirk Iron Furnace on US 1 was established by Andrew and Elias Elliott, who learned their iron-making skills in Muirkirk, Scotland.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] They produced some of the best-quality pig iron in the country and supplied the U.S.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] Army with cannons, shot, wheels, and other iron products during the Revolutionary War and the Civil War.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] By 1730, Post Road (now part of US 1) was the main thoroughfare through Beltsville.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] Though crude, it made stagecoach travel possible.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] In 1783, Gabriel Peterson Van Horn established a stage line and built the Van Horn Tavern on Odell Road, where passengers could spend the night as they traveled between Baltimore and Washington.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] Beltsville has a distinguished Revolutionary War hero as its native son.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] Brigadier General Rezin Beall, who was born on Turkey Flight Plantation on Old Gunpowder Road in 1723, prevented a British invasion at Drum Point on the Chesapeake Bay with only 100 men.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] He is credited with the fact that there are no Revolutionary War battlefields in Maryland.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] In 1835 one of the first rail lines in the country, the Washington branch of the B&O Railroad (Baltimore & Ohio), was built through Prince George's County.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] Coming from Baltimore, the line entered the county at Laurel and ran southwesterly to Bladensburg, then into Washington.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] B&O established a rail stop and freight depot on land purchased from a tobacco farmer named Trueman Belt, and they named the place after him.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] The new community of Beltsville was doubly blessed, for the Baltimore-Washington Turnpike crossed the rail line there.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] It soon became a thriving little trading center, eclipsing the older community of Vansville further north on the pike.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] The original area developed haphazardly and consisted of a few residences, two churches, several small stores, a blacksmith, and a wheelwright.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] In 1891, the Beltsville Land Improvement Company was chartered and over the next thirty years developed the South Beltsville subdivision as a grid of streets.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] The developers sold the lots to individual owners and placed restrictive covenants on the deeds, including forbidding the manufacture or sale of alcohol and the sale of any property to an African American.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] Beltsville was marketed to professionals who wanted to escape the congestion of Washington and was developed with a mixture of Victorian-style houses and Colonial Revival houses.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] The community grew further when an electric railway was extended to Beltsville.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] The railway began as the Berwyn and Laurel Electric Railroad, but after suffering from financial difficulties it was acquired by the City and Suburban Railway.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] Located to the west of the railroad, along the line of present-day Rhode Island Avenue, the streetcar line served as the nucleus for additional subdivisions.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] These areas continued to develop slowly throughout the 1930s and 1940s with the construction of modest side-gable residences.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] Development continued after the introduction of the automobile, but it was not until after World War II that intensive development came to the Beltsville area.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] As the federal government grew, in 1910 the U.S.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] Department of Agriculture (USDA) began to purchase land in Beltsville for its Agricultural Research Service, the main in-house research arm of the USDA.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] Wallace Beltsville Agricultural Research Center (BARC).
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] The first parcel acquired was 375 acres (1.5 km2) of the Walnut Grange Plantation with its historic "Butterfly House".
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] The Center eventually encompassed 14,600 acres (59 km2) and became the largest and most prominent center of agricultural science research in the world.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] There are a number of historic homes and buildings still standing in Beltsville.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] One of the largest of the older buildings, built in 1880, was the three-story Ammendale Normal Institute, which was destroyed by fire in 1998.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] In 2003 Kevin Kennedy started a group which aimed to have Beltsville incorporate into its own municipality.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] By 2004 the 12-member group, named Committee to Incorporate Beltsville, advocated for getting the issue on the ballot.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] By late 2004 the group began efforts to collect 3,000 signatures on a petition so the issue can be put up for election; this would represent about one quarter of the persons in Beltsville who were registered to vote.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] By the deadline in March 2005 they failed to get sufficient signatures as they only had 2,000.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] The following is a list of historic sites in Beltsville and identified by the Maryland-National Capital Park and Planning Commission: African-American Heritage Sites at nearby Rossville are listed at Muirkirk, Maryland.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] Prince George's County Police Department District 6 Station in Beltsville CDP serves the community.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] Postal Service operates the Beltsville Post Office.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] The Department of State operates the Beltsville Information Management Center.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] The United States Secret Service James J.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] Rowley Training Center is nicknamed “Beltsville” but is actually located in adjacent Laurel.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] Some of the most important research and bureaucratic facilities of the United States Department of Agriculture Agricultural Research Service (USDA ARS) are located here.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] There are three parochial schools in Beltsville: Augsburg Academy (Lutheran), St Joseph's School (Roman Catholic of the Roman Catholic Diocese of Washington), and Beltsville Seventh-day Adventist (SDA).
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] Prince George's County Memorial Library System operates the Beltsville Branch.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/beltsville-maryland] Experimental post-hardcore band Thrice recorded the album *The Illusion of Safety* here and dedicated a song to the town, named "The Beltsville Crucible".
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] A **cultivar** is a kind of cultivated plant that people have selected for desired traits and which retains those traits when propagated.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Methods used to propagate cultivars include division, root and stem cuttings, offsets, grafting, tissue culture, or carefully controlled seed production.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Most cultivars arise from deliberate human manipulation, but some originate from wild plants that have distinctive characteristics.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Cultivar names are chosen according to rules of the International Code of Nomenclature for Cultivated Plants (ICNCP), and not all cultivated plants qualify as cultivars.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Horticulturists generally believe the word *cultivar* was coined as a term meaning "**cultivated variety**".
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Popular ornamental plants like roses, camellias, daffodils, rhododendrons, and azaleas are commonly cultivars produced by breeding and selection or as sports, for floral colour or size, plant form, or other desirable characteristics.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Similarly, the world's agricultural food crops are almost exclusively cultivars that have been selected for characters such as improved yield, flavour, and resistance to disease.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Since the advent of genetic engineering in the 1970s and the rise of its application in crop breeding in the 1980s, very few wild plants are used as commercial food sources.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Trees used in forestry are also special selections grown for their enhanced quality and yield of timber, for example American timber company Weyerhaeuser is the leading grower of genetically modified Douglas-fir trees, one of the most commonly harvested trees.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Cultivars form a major part of Liberty Hyde Bailey's broader group, the cultigen, which is defined as a plant whose origin or selection is primarily due to intentional human activity.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] A cultivar is not the same as a botanical variety, which is a taxonomic rank below subspecies, and there are differences in the rules for creating and using the names of botanical varieties and cultivars.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Since the creation of the Plant Patent Act of 1930 the naming of cultivars has been complicated by the use of statutory patents for plants and recognition of plant breeders' rights.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] The International Union for the Protection of New Varieties of Plants (UPOV – French: *Union internationale pour la protection des obtentions végétales*) offers legal protection of plant cultivars to persons or organisations that introduce new cultivars to commerce.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] UPOV requires that a cultivar be "distinct", "uniform", and "stable".
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] To be "distinct", it must have characters that easily distinguish it from any other named cultivar.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] To be "uniform" and "stable", the cultivar must retain these characters in repeated propagation.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] The naming of cultivars is an important aspect of cultivated plant taxonomy, and the correct naming of a cultivar is prescribed by the Rules and Recommendations of the *International Code of Nomenclature for Cultivated Plants* (ICNCP, often called the *Cultivated Plant Code*).
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] A cultivar is given a cultivar name, which consists of the scientific Latin botanical name followed by a cultivar epithet.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] The cultivar epithet is usually in a vernacular language, and must be so for cultivars named after 1 January 1959.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] The word *cultivar* originated from the need to distinguish between wild plants and those with characteristics that arose in cultivation, presently denominated *cultigens*.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] This distinction dates to the Greek philosopher Theophrastus (370–285 BC), the "Father of Botany", who was keenly aware of this difference.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] The International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants uses as its starting point for modern botanical nomenclature the Latin names in Linnaeus' (1707–1778) *Species Plantarum* (tenth edition) and *Genera Plantarum* (fifth edition).
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] In *Species Plantarum*, Linnaeus enumerated all plants known to him, either directly or from his extensive reading.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] He recognised the rank of varietas (botanical "variety", a rank below that of species and subspecies) and he indicated these varieties with letters of the Greek alphabet, such as α, β, and δ, before the varietal name, rather than using the abbreviation "var." as is the present convention.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Most of the varieties that Linnaeus enumerated were of "garden" origin rather than being wild plants.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] In time the need to distinguish between wild plants and those with variations that had been cultivated increased.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] In the nineteenth century many "garden-derived" plants were given horticultural names, sometimes in Latin and sometimes in a vernacular language.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] From *circa* the 1900s, cultivated plants in Europe were recognised in the Scandinavian, Germanic, and Slavic literature as *stamm* or *sorte*, but these words could not be used internationally because, by international agreement, any new denominations had to be in Latin.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] In the twentieth century an improved international nomenclature was proposed for cultivated plants.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] In that essay, Bailey used only the rank of species for the cultigen, but it was obvious to him that many domesticated plants were more like botanical varieties than species, and that realisation appears to have motivated the suggestion of the new category of *cultivar*.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] It is generally assumed to be a blend of ***culti**vated* and ***var**iety* but Bailey never explicitly stated his choice of etymology, and it has been suggested that the word is actually a blend of ***culti**gen* and ***var**iety*.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] The neologism *cultivar* was promoted as "euphonious" and "free from ambiguity".
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] The first *Cultivated Plant Code* of 1953 subsequently commended its use, and by 1960 it had achieved common international acceptance.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] The words *cultigen* and *cultivar* may be confused with each other.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] A *cultigen* is any plant that is deliberately selected for or altered in cultivation, as opposed to an *indigen*; the *Cultivated Plant Code* states that cultigens are "maintained as recognisable entities solely by continued propagation".
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Cultigens can have names at any of many taxonomic ranks, including those of grex, species, cultivar group, variety, form, and cultivar; and they may be plants that have been altered in cultivation, including by genetic modification, but have not been formally denominated.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] A cultigen or a component of a cultigen can be accepted as a cultivar if it is recognisable and has stable characters.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Therefore, all cultivars are cultigens, because they are cultivated, but not all cultigens are cultivars, because some cultigens have not been formally distinguished and named as cultivars.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] The *Code* then defines a *cultivar* as a "taxonomic unit within the classification category of cultivar".
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] This is the sense of *cultivar* that is most generally understood and which is used as a general definition.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] A cultivar may be given a vernacular name or a number.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Which plants are chosen to be named as cultivars is simply a matter of convenience as the category was created to serve the practical needs of horticulture, agriculture, and forestry.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Members of a particular cultivar are not necessarily genetically identical.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] The *Cultivated Plant Code* emphasizes that different cultivated plants may be accepted as different cultivars, even if they have the same genome, while cultivated plants with different genomes may be regarded as the same cultivar.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] The production of cultivars generally entails considerable human involvement although in a few cases it may be as little as simply selecting variation from plants growing in the wild (whether by collecting growing tissue to propagate from or by gathering seed).
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Cultivars generally occur as ornamentals and food crops: *Malus* 'Granny Smith' and *Malus* 'Red Delicious' are cultivars of apples propagated by cuttings or grafting, *Lactuca* 'Red Sails' and *Lactuca* 'Great Lakes' are lettuce cultivars propagated by seeds.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Named cultivars of *Hosta* and *Hemerocallis* plants are cultivars produced by micropropagation or division.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Cultivars that are produced asexually are genetically identical and known as clones; this includes plants propagated by division, layering, cuttings, grafts, and budding.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] The propagating material may be taken from a particular part of the plant, such as a lateral branch, or from a particular phase of the life cycle, such as a juvenile leaf, or from aberrant growth as occurs with witch's broom.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Plants whose distinctive characters are derived from the presence of an intracellular organism may also form a cultivar provided the characters are reproduced reliably from generation to generation.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Plants of the same chimera (which have mutant tissues close to normal tissue) or graft-chimeras (which have vegetative tissue from different kinds of plants and which originate by grafting) may also constitute a cultivar.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Some cultivars "come true from seed", retaining their distinguishing characteristics when grown from seed.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Such plants are termed a "variety", "selection", or "strain" but these are ambiguous and confusing words that are best avoided.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] In general, asexually propagated cultivars grown from seeds produce highly variable seedling plants, and should not be labelled with, or sold under, the parent cultivar's name.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Seed-raised cultivars may be produced by uncontrolled pollination when characteristics that are distinct, uniform and stable are passed from parents to progeny.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Some are produced as "lines" that are produced by repeated self-fertilisation or inbreeding or "multilines" that are made up of several closely related lines.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Sometimes they are F1 hybrids which are the result of a deliberate repeatable single cross between two pure lines.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] A few F2 hybrid seed cultivars also exist, such as *Achillea* 'Summer Berries'.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Some cultivars are agamospermous plants, which retain their genetic composition and characteristics under reproduction.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Occasionally cultivars are raised from seed of a specially selected provenance – for example the seed may be taken from plants that are resistant to a particular disease.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Genetically modified plants with characteristics resulting from the deliberate implantation of genetic material from a different germplasm may form a cultivar.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] However, the International Code of Nomenclature for Cultivated Plants notes, "In practice such an assemblage is often marketed from one or more lines or multilines that have been genetically modified.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Cultivars may be selected because of a change in the ploidy level of a plant which may produce more desirable characteristics.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Every cultivar has a unique name within its denomination class (which is almost always the genus).
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Names of cultivars are regulated by the *International Code of Nomenclature for Cultivated Plants*, and may be registered with an International Cultivar Registration Authority (ICRA).
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] There are sometimes separate registration authorities for different plant types such as roses and camellias.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] In addition, cultivars may be associated with commercial marketing names referred to in the *Cultivated Plant Code* as "trade designations" (see below).
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] A *cultivar name* consists of a botanical name (of a genus, species, infraspecific taxon, interspecific hybrid or intergeneric hybrid) followed by a cultivar epithet.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] The cultivar epithet is enclosed by single quotes; it should not be italicised if the botanical name is italicised; and each of the words within the epithet is capitalised (with some permitted exceptions such as conjunctions).
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] It is permissible to place a cultivar epithet after a common name provided the common name is botanically unambiguous.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Cultivar epithets published before 1 January 1959 were often given a Latin form and can be readily confused with the specific epithets in botanical names; after that date, newly coined cultivar epithets must be in a modern vernacular language to distinguish them from botanical epithets.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] For example, the full cultivar name of the King Edward potato is *Solanum tuberosum* 'King Edward'.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] 'King Edward' is the cultivar epithet, which, according to the Rules of the *Cultivated Plant Code*, is bounded by single quotation marks.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Although "cv." has not been permitted by the International Code of Nomenclature for Cultivated Plants since the 1995 edition, it is still widely used and recommended by other authorities.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Where several very similar cultivars exist they can be associated into a *Group* (formerly *Cultivar-group*).
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] As Group names are used with cultivar names it is necessary to understand their way of presentation.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Group names are presented in normal type and the first letter of each word capitalised as for cultivars, but they are not placed in single quotes.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] When used in a name, the first letter of the word "Group" is itself capitalised.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Since the 1990s there has been an increasing use of legal protection for newly produced cultivars.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Plant breeders expect legal protection for the cultivars they produce.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] According to proponents of such protections, if other growers can immediately propagate and sell these cultivars as soon as they come on the market, the breeder's benefit is largely lost.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Legal protection for cultivars is obtained through the use of Plant breeders' rights and plant Patents but the specific legislation and procedures needed to take advantage of this protection vary from country to country.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] The use of legal protection for cultivars can be controversial, particularly for food crops that are staples in developing countries, or for plants selected from the wild and propagated for sale without any additional breeding work; some people consider this practice unethical.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] The formal scientific name of a cultivar, like *Solanum tuberosum* 'King Edward', is a way of uniquely designating a particular kind of plant.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] This scientific name is in the public domain and cannot be legally protected.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Plant retailers may wish to increase their share of the market, and one way of doing this is to replace the Latin scientific names on plant labels in retail outlets with appealing marketing names that are easy to use, pronounce, and remember.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Marketing names lie outside the scope of the *Cultivated Plant Code* which refers to them as "trade designations".
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] If a retailer or wholesaler has the sole legal rights to a marketing name then that may offer a sales advantage.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Plants protected by plant breeders' rights (PBR) may have a "true" cultivar name – the accepted scientific name in the public domain – and a "commercial synonym" – an additional marketing name that is legally protected.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] An example would be *Rosa* Fascination='Poulmax', in which *Rosa* is the genus, Fascination is the trade designation, and 'Poulmax' is scientific cultivar name.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Because a name that is attractive in one language may have less appeal in another country, a plant may be given different selling names from country to country.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Quoting the original cultivar name allows the correct identification of cultivars around the world.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] The main body coordinating plant breeders' rights is the International Union for the Protection of New Varieties of Plants (*Union internationale pour la protection des obtentions végétales*, UPOV) and this organisation maintains a database of new cultivars protected by PBR in all countries.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] An *International Cultivar Registration Authority* (ICRA) is a voluntary, non-statutory organisation appointed by the *Commission for Nomenclature and Cultivar Registration* of the International Society of Horticultural Science.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] ICRAs are generally formed by societies and institutions specializing in particular plant genera such as *Dahlia* or *Rhododendron* and are currently located in Europe, North America, China, India, Singapore, Australia, New Zealand, South Africa and Puerto Rico.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Each ICRA produces an annual report and its reappointment is considered every four years.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] The main task is to maintain a register of the names within the group of interest and where possible this is published and placed in the public domain.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] One major aim is to prevent the duplication of cultivar and Group epithets within a genus, as well as ensuring that names are in accord with the latest edition of the *Cultivated Plant Code*.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] In this way, over the last 50 years or so, ICRAs have contributed to the stability of cultivated plant nomenclature.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] In recent times many ICRAs have also recorded trade designations and trademarks used in labelling plant material, to avoid confusion with established names.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] New names and other relevant data are collected by and submitted to the ICRA and in most cases there is no cost.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] The ICRA then checks each new epithet to ensure that it has not been used before and that it conforms with the *Cultivated Plant Code*.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Each ICRA also ensures that new names are formally established (i.e. published in hard copy, with a description in a dated publication).
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] They record details about the plant, such as parentage, the names of those concerned with its development and introduction, and a basic description highlighting its distinctive characters.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] ICRAs are not responsible for assessing the distinctiveness of the plant in question.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/cultivars] Most ICRAs can be contacted electronically and many maintain web sites for an up-to-date listing.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/germplasm-resources-information-network] GRIN has extended its role to manage information on the germplasm reposits of insect (invertebrate), microbial, and animal species (see sub-projects).
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/germplasm-resources-information-network] The site is a resource for identifying taxonomic information (scientific names) as well as common names on more than 500,000 accessions (distinct varieties, cultivars etc.) of plants covering 10,000 species; both economically important ones and wild species.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/germplasm-resources-information-network] It profiles plants that are invasive or noxious weeds, threatened or endangered, giving out data on worldwide distribution of its habitat; as well as passport information.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/germplasm-resources-information-network] GRIN also incorporates an Economic Plants Database.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/germplasm-resources-information-network] The network is maintained by GRIN's Database Management Unit (GRIN/DBMU).
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/germplasm-resources-information-network] GRIN is under the oversight of National Germplasm Resources Laboratory (NGRL) in Beltsville, Maryland, which in 1990 replaced its forerunner, the Germplasm Services Laboratory (GSL), that had formerly run GRIN.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/germplasm-resources-information-network] Since November, 2015 GRIN has been running on GRIN-Global software produced by a collaborative project between the USDA and the Global Crop Diversity Trust.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/germplasm] In the United States, germplasm resources are regulated by the National Genetic Resources Program (NGRP), created by the U.S. congress in 1990.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/germplasm] In addition the web server The Germplasm Resources Information Network (GRIN) provides information about germplasms as they pertain to agriculture production.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/germplasm] Specifically for plants, there is the U.S.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/germplasm] National Plant Germplasm System (NPGS) which holds > 450,000 accessions with 10,000 species of the 85 most commonly grown crops.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/germplasm] Many accessions held are international species, and NPGS distributes germplasm resources internationally.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/germplasm] As genetic information moves largely online there is a transition in germplasm information from a physical location (seed banks, cryopreserving) to online platforms containing genetic sequences.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/germplasm] In addition there are issues in the collection germplasm information and where they are shared.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/germplasm] Historically some germplasm information had been collected in developing countries and then shared to researchers who then sell the donor country the original germplasm that they altered.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/germplasm] There is a lack of compensation to the donor countries and this is an issue.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/germplasm] Effective Germplasm work includes the collection, storage, analysis, documentation, and exchange of genetic information.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/germplasm] This information can be stored as accessions, which is DNA sequence information, or live cells/tissues that can be preserved.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/germplasm] However, only about 5% of current germplasm resources are living samples.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/germplasm] For live cells/tissues, germplasm resources can be stored *ex situ* in seed banks, botanic gardens, or through cryopreservation.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/germplasm] Cryopreservation is the process of storing germplasm at very low temperatures, such as liquid nitrogen.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/germplasm] This process ensures that cells do not degrade and keeps the germplasm intact.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/germplasm] In addition, resources can be stored in situ such as the natural area the species was found.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/germplasm] About 10,000 years ago is when humans began to domesticate plant species for the purpose of food, seeds, and vegetation.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/germplasm] Since then, agriculture has been a staple for human civilizations and plant breeding has allowed more genetic diversity and a more diverse gene pool.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/germplasm] Germplasm resources allow for more genetic assets to be used and integrated for agricultural systems for plant breeding and bringing about new varieties.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/germplasm] In addition, researchers are looking at crop wild relatives (CWRs) that could expand gene pools of crop species and provide more ability to select target traits.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/germplasm] Furthermore, we are currently facing a biodiversity crisis event that is caused by human activities and industrialization.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/germplasm] Many plants and animals have gone extinct due to losing their habitat, their habitat being degraded with contaminants, and climate change.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/germplasm] Germplasm resources are a way to conserve the pre-existing biological diversity and to possibly regenerate habitats.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/germplasm] By storing this genetic information there is data about what species are present including plants, animals, bacteria, and fungi and what a complete ecosystem in specific areas look like.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] The **Crop Trust**, officially known as the **Global Crop Diversity Trust**, is an international nonprofit organization with a secretariat in Bonn, Germany.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] Its mission is to conserve and make available the world's crop diversity for food security.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] Established in 2004, the Crop Trust is the only organization whose sole mission is to safeguard the world's crop diversity for future food security.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] Through an endowment fund for crop diversity, the Crop Trust provides financial support for key international and national genebanks that hold collections of diversity for food crops available under the International Treaty for Plant Genetic Resources for Food and Agriculture (ITPGRFA).
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] The organization also provides tools and support for the efficient management of genebanks, facilitates coordination between conserving institutions, and organizes final backup of crop seeds in the Svalbard Global Seed Vault.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] Since its establishment, the Crop Trust has raised more than US$300 million for the Crop Diversity Endowment Fund and supports conservation work in over 80 countries.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] Crop diversity is the biological foundation of agriculture, and is the raw material plant breeders and farmers use to adapt crop varieties to pests and diseases.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] In the future, this crop diversity will play a central role in helping agriculture adjust to climate change and adapt to water and energy constraints.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] In 1996, the UN Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) recognized the need for global coordination for the conservation of the world's crop diversity.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] At a conference organized by the FAO, 150 countries launched a Global Plan of Action to coordinate efforts at halting the loss of the world's agrobiodiversity.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] The Global Plan of Action formed a major pillar of what would become the International Treaty on Plant Genetic Resources for Food and Agriculture, known as the Plant Treaty.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] The Plant Treaty brings the diversity of 64 food and forage crops into a multilateral system where the genetic material is protected and accessible to all who needed it.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] To protect the collections that housed that genetic material, however, a stable system of funding was needed.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] To partly address this need, the Crop Trust was established in October 2004.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] Its mission was to help build a global system of *ex situ* crop diversity conservation, funded through an endowment for crop diversity.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] The Plant Treaty recognizes the endowment fund as an essential element of its funding strategy and confirms the autonomy of the Crop Trust as a scientific organization in raising and disbursing funds.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] Geoff Hawtin was appointed the Interim Executive Director of the new organization, housed at the FAO headquarters in Rome, Italy.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] The Crop Trust began its work gathering contributions for the endowment fund from various foundations, corporations, and governments that had ratified the Plant Treaty.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] In 2007, the Crop Trust signed its first long-term grant agreement with the International Rice Research Institute (IRRI) in Los Baños, Philippines.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] In 2005, Cary Fowler was appointed the first permanent Crop Trust Executive Director.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] In 2011, the Crop Trust launched the Crop Wild Relatives Project, a 10-year project to collect and conserve crop wild relatives, a project funded by the Government of Norway.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] In 2012, the Crop Trust appointed Marie Haga as the new Crop Trust Executive Director.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] A new target for the Crop Trust endowment fund was set at US$850 million to finance a global system for the conservation of crop diversity, centered around key international, regional and national collections, as well as the Svalbard Global Seed Vault.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] In 2013, the Crop Trust opened its new headquarters in Bonn, Germany, through a hosting agreement with the Government of Germany.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] Shortly thereafter, the Crop Trust launched the five-year CGIAR Genebank CRP, taking on financial responsibility and oversight for the 11 CGIAR genebanks.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] In 2017, the CGIAR Genebank Platform replaced the Genebank CRP program and the Food Forever Initiative was launched to raise awareness of efforts to achieve Target 2.5 of the United Nations Sustainable Development Goals.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] In 2018, the Crop Trust signed the first long-term funding agreement with the IRRI genebank, pledging to fully fund essential operations in perpetuity.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] The Crop Trust celebrated its 15th anniversary in 2019 and crossed the US$300 million threshold in the endowment fund.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] In 2020, Stefan Schmitz was appointed Executive Director.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] With support from the German government, the Crop Trust launched the Seeds4Resilience Project project in 2020.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] The project will upgrade five national genebanks in sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] In February 2020, the Svalbard Global Seed Vault reached one million accessions of seed samples for more than 6,000 species.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] The Crop Trust is headquartered in Bonn, Germany, after relocating there from Rome, Italy.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] The executive board is chaired by Catherine Bertini.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] The Crop Trust's Donors' Council is chaired by Dr.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] Main donors include: Australia, Canada, Germany, Ireland, Norway, Sweden, Switzerland, United Kingdom, United States, the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation, and the Grains Research and Development Corporation (Australia).
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] A number of developing countries have also provided support, including Egypt, Ethiopia and India.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] Further contributions have been received from private corporations, foundations, industry associations, and from private individuals.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] Since its establishment, the Crop Trust has funded work in over 80 countries, and made its first grant for long-term conservation of a collection in late 2006.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] By 2011, the Crop Trust had established in-perpetuity support (i.e. grants funded through the Crop Trust's endowment) for collections of 15 crops: rice, cassava, wheat, barley, faba bean, pearl millet, maize, forages, banana, aroids, grass pea, sorghum, yam and lentil.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] In 2007, the Crop Trust began a global initiative to rescue threatened, high-priority collections of crop diversity in developing countries and to support information systems to improve their conservation and availability.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] These efforts included providing support to developing countries and international agricultural research centers to deposit shipments of seed samples in the Svalbard Global Seed Vault for safety duplication purposes.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] In 2010, the Crop Trust launched a global 10-year program to find, gather, catalog and save the wild relatives of 22 major food crops.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] These wild species contain untapped diversity to help address future challenges to agriculture.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] The Crop Trust joined the Government of Norway and the Nordic Gene Bank in the 2008 establishment of the Svalbard Global Seed Vault, a "fail-safe" facility located at Svalbard, Norway.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] The Seed Vault provides long-term storage of duplicates of seeds conserved in genebanks around the world.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] This provides security of the world's food supply against the loss of seeds in genebanks due to mismanagement, accident, equipment failures, funding cuts, and natural disasters.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] It is designed to hold the seeds of some 4.5 million samples of different varieties of agricultural crops.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] Primarily through the endowment fund, the Crop Trust provides most of the annual operating costs for the facility.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/global-crop-diversity-trust] With support from donors, the Crop Trust also assists selected genebanks in packaging and shipping seeds to the Seed Vault.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/international-plant-names-index] The **International Plant Names Index** (**IPNI**) describes itself as "a database of the names and associated basic bibliographical details of seed plants, ferns and lycophytes." Coverage of plant names is best at the rank of species and genus.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/international-plant-names-index] It includes basic bibliographical details associated with the names.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/international-plant-names-index] Its goals include eliminating the need for repeated reference to primary sources for basic bibliographic information about plant names.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/international-plant-names-index] The IPNI also maintains a list of standardized author abbreviations.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/international-plant-names-index] These were initially based on Brummitt & Powell (1992), but new names and abbreviations are continually added.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/international-plant-names-index] IPNI is the product of a collaboration between The Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew (Index Kewensis), The Harvard University Herbaria (Gray Herbarium Index), and the Australian National Herbarium (APNI).
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/international-plant-names-index] The IPNI database is a collection of the names registered by the three cooperating institutions, and they work towards standardizing the information.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/international-plant-names-index] The standard of author abbreviations recommended by the *International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants* is Brummitt and Powell's *Authors of Plant Names*.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/international-plant-names-index] A digital and continually updated list of authors and abbreviations can be consulted online at IPNI.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/international-plant-names-index] The IPNI provides names that have appeared in scholarly publications, with the objective of providing an index of published names rather than prescribing the accepted botanical nomenclature.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] The majority of animal species are invertebrates; one estimate puts the figure at 97%.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Many invertebrate taxa have a greater number and diversity of species than the entire subphylum of Vertebrata.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Invertebrates vary widely in size, from 10 μm (0.0004 in) myxozoans to the 9–10 m (30–33 ft) colossal squid.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Some so-called invertebrates, such as the Tunicata and Cephalochordata, are actually sister chordate subphyla to Vertebrata, being more closely related to vertebrates than to other invertebrates.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] This makes the "invertebrates" paraphyletic, so the term has no significance in taxonomy.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] The word "invertebrate" comes from the Latin word *vertebra*, which means a joint in general, and sometimes specifically a joint from the spinal column of a vertebrate.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] The jointed aspect of *vertebra* is derived from the concept of turning, expressed in the root *verto* or *vorto*, to turn.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] The prefix *in-* means "not" or "without".
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] The term *invertebrates* does not describe a taxon in the same way that Arthropoda, Vertebrata or Manidae do.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Each of those terms describes a valid taxon, phylum, subphylum or family.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] "Invertebrata" is a term of convenience, not a taxon; it has very little circumscriptional significance except within the Chordata.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] The Vertebrata as a subphylum comprises such a small proportion of the Metazoa that to speak of the kingdom Animalia in terms of "Vertebrata" and "Invertebrata" has limited practicality.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] In the more formal taxonomy of Animalia other attributes that logically should precede the presence or absence of the vertebral column in constructing a cladogram, for example, the presence of a notochord.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] That would at least circumscribe the Chordata.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] However, even the notochord would be a less fundamental criterion than aspects of embryological development and symmetry or perhaps Bauplan.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Despite this, the concept of *invertebrates* as a taxon of animals has persisted for over a century among the laity, and within the zoological community and in its literature it remains in use as a term of convenience for animals that are not members of the Vertebrata.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] The following text reflects earlier scientific understanding of the term and of those animals which have constituted it.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] According to this understanding, invertebrates do not possess a skeleton of bone, either internal or external.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Many have fluid-filled, hydrostatic skeletons, like jellyfish or worms.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Others have hard exoskeletons, outer shells like those of insects and crustaceans.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] The most familiar invertebrates include the Protozoa, Porifera, Coelenterata, Platyhelminthes, Nematoda, Annelida, Echinodermata, Mollusca and Arthropoda.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Arthropoda include insects, crustaceans and arachnids.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] By far the largest number of described invertebrate species are insects.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] The following table lists the number of described extant species for major invertebrate groups as estimated in the IUCN Red List of Threatened Species, 2014.3.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] The IUCN estimates that 66,178 extant vertebrate species have been described, which means that over 95% of the described animal species in the world are invertebrates.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] The trait that is common to all invertebrates is the absence of a vertebral column (backbone): this creates a distinction between invertebrates and vertebrates.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] The distinction is one of convenience only; it is not based on any clear biologically homologous trait, any more than the common trait of having wings functionally unites insects, bats, and birds, or than not having wings unites tortoises, snails and sponges.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Being animals, invertebrates are heterotrophs, and require sustenance in the form of the consumption of other organisms.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] With a few exceptions, such as the Porifera, invertebrates generally have bodies composed of differentiated tissues.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] There is also typically a digestive chamber with one or two openings to the exterior.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] The body plans of most multicellular organisms exhibit some form of symmetry, whether radial, bilateral, or spherical.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] A minority, however, exhibit no symmetry.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] One example of asymmetric invertebrates includes all gastropod species.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] This is easily seen in snails and sea snails, which have helical shells.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Slugs appear externally symmetrical, but their pneumostome (breathing hole) is located on the right side.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Other gastropods develop external asymmetry, such as *Glaucus atlanticus* that develops asymmetrical cerata as they mature.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] The origin of gastropod asymmetry is a subject of scientific debate.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Other examples of asymmetry are found in fiddler crabs and hermit crabs.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] They often have one claw much larger than the other.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] If a male fiddler loses its large claw, it will grow another on the opposite side after moulting.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Neurons differ in invertebrates from mammalian cells.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Invertebrates cells fire in response to similar stimuli as mammals, such as tissue trauma, high temperature, or changes in pH.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] The first invertebrate in which a neuron cell was identified was the medicinal leech, *Hirudo medicinalis*.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Learning and memory using nociceptors have been described in the sea hare, *Aplysia*.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Mollusk neurons are able to detect increasing pressures and tissue trauma.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Neurons have been identified in a wide range of invertebrate species, including annelids, molluscs, nematodes and arthropods.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] One type of invertebrate respiratory system is the open respiratory system composed of spiracles, tracheae, and tracheoles that terrestrial arthropods have to transport metabolic gases to and from tissues.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] The distribution of spiracles can vary greatly among the many orders of insects, but in general each segment of the body can have only one pair of spiracles, each of which connects to an atrium and has a relatively large tracheal tube behind it.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] The tracheae are invaginations of the cuticular exoskeleton that branch (anastomose) throughout the body with diameters from only a few micrometres up to 0.8 mm.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] The smallest tubes, tracheoles, penetrate cells and serve as sites of diffusion for water, oxygen, and carbon dioxide.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Gas may be conducted through the respiratory system by means of active ventilation or passive diffusion.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Unlike vertebrates, insects do not generally carry oxygen in their haemolymph.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] A tracheal tube may contain ridge-like circumferential rings of taenidia in various geometries such as loops or helices.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] In the head, thorax, or abdomen, tracheae may also be connected to air sacs.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Many insects, such as grasshoppers and bees, which actively pump the air sacs in their abdomen, are able to control the flow of air through their body.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] In some aquatic insects, the tracheae exchange gas through the body wall directly, in the form of a gill, or function essentially as normal, via a plastron.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Despite being internal, the tracheae of arthropods are shed during moulting (ecdysis).
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Only vertebrate animals have ears, though many invertebrates detect sound using other kinds of sense organs.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] In insects, tympanal organs are used to hear distant sounds.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] They are located either on the head or elsewhere, depending on the insect family.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] The tympanal organs of some insects are extremely sensitive, offering acute hearing beyond that of most other animals.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] The female cricket fly *Ormia ochracea* has tympanal organs on each side of her abdomen.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] They are connected by a thin bridge of exoskeleton and they function like a tiny pair of eardrums, but, because they are linked, they provide acute directional information.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] The fly uses her "ears" to detect the call of her host, a male cricket.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Depending on where the song of the cricket is coming from, the fly's hearing organs will reverberate at slightly different frequencies.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] This difference may be as little as 50 billionths of a second, but it is enough to allow the fly to home in directly on a singing male cricket and parasitise it.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Simpler structures allow other arthropods to detect near-field sounds.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Spiders and cockroaches, for example, have hairs on their legs, which are used for detecting sound.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Caterpillars of the Monarch butterfly have shown behavioral responses to airborne vibration (sound).
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Experiments have shown that the detection of sound is received through a pair of 450 micrometre long hairs called trichoid sensilla located on their upper prothorax.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Response has been shown to the flight sounds of insect predators and parasitoids.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Like vertebrates, most invertebrates reproduce at least partly through sexual reproduction.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] They produce specialized reproductive cells that undergo meiosis to produce smaller, motile spermatozoa or larger, non-motile ova.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] These fuse to form zygotes, which develop into new individuals.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Others are capable of asexual reproduction, or sometimes, both methods of reproduction.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Extensive research with model invertebrate species such as *Drosophila melanogaster* and *Caenorhabditis elegans* has contributed much to our understanding of meiosis and reproduction.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] However, beyond the few model systems, the modes of reproduction found in invertebrates show incredible diversity.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] In one extreme example, it is estimated that 10% of orbatid mite species have persisted without sexual reproduction and have reproduced asexually for more than 400 million years.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Invertebrates have an extremely diverse array of reproductive systems, the only commonality may be that they all lay eggs.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Also, aside from cephalopods and arthropods, nearly all other invertebrates exhibit external fertilization.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Social behavior is widespread in invertebrates, including cockroaches, termites, aphids, thrips, ants, bees, Passalidae, Acari, spiders, and more.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Social interaction is particularly salient in eusocial species but applies to other invertebrates as well.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Insects recognize information transmitted by other insects.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] The term invertebrates covers several phyla.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] One of these are the sponges (Porifera).
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] They were long thought to have diverged from other animals early.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] They lack the complex organization found in most other phyla.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Their cells are differentiated, but in most cases not organized into distinct tissues.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Sponges typically feed by drawing in water through pores.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Some speculate that sponges are not so primitive, but may instead be secondarily simplified.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] The Ctenophora and the Cnidaria, which includes sea anemones, corals, and jellyfish, are radially symmetric and have digestive chambers with a single opening, which serves as both the mouth and the anus.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Both have distinct tissues, but they are not organized into organs.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] There are only two main germ layers, the ectoderm and endoderm, with only scattered cells between them.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] As such, they are sometimes called diploblastic.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] The Echinodermata are radially symmetric and exclusively marine, including starfish (Asteroidea), sea urchins, (Echinoidea), brittle stars (Ophiuroidea), sea cucumbers (Holothuroidea) and feather stars (Crinoidea).
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] The largest animal phylum is also included within invertebrates: the Arthropoda, including insects, spiders, crabs, and their kin.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] All these organisms have a body divided into repeating segments, typically with paired appendages.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] In addition, they possess a hardened exoskeleton that is periodically shed during growth.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Two smaller phyla, the Onychophora and Tardigrada, are close relatives of the arthropods and share some traits with them, excluding the hardened exoskeleton.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] The Nematoda, or roundworms, are perhaps the second largest animal phylum, and are also invertebrates.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Roundworms are typically microscopic, and occur in nearly every environment where there is water.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Smaller phyla related to them are the Kinorhyncha, Priapulida, and Loricifera.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] These groups have a reduced coelom, called a pseudocoelom.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Other invertebrates include the Nemertea, or ribbon worms, and the Sipuncula.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Another phylum is Platyhelminthes, the flatworms.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] These were originally considered primitive, but it now appears they developed from more complex ancestors.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Flatworms are acoelomates, lacking a body cavity, as are their closest relatives, the microscopic Gastrotricha.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] The Rotifera, or rotifers, are common in aqueous environments.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Invertebrates also include the Acanthocephala, or spiny-headed worms, the Gnathostomulida, Micrognathozoa, and the Cycliophora.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Also included are two of the most successful animal phyla, the Mollusca and Annelida.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] The former, which is the second-largest animal phylum by number of described species, includes animals such as snails, clams, and squids, and the latter comprises the segmented worms, such as earthworms and leeches.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] These two groups have long been considered close relatives because of the common presence of trochophore larvae, but the annelids were considered closer to the arthropods because they are both segmented.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Now, this is generally considered convergent evolution, owing to many morphological and genetic differences between the two phyla.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Among lesser phyla of invertebrates are the Hemichordata, or acorn worms, and the Chaetognatha, or arrow worms.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Other phyla include Acoelomorpha, Brachiopoda, Bryozoa, Entoprocta, Phoronida, and Xenoturbellida.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Invertebrates can be classified into several main categories, some of which are taxonomically obsolescent or debatable, but still used as terms of convenience.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Each however appears in its own article at the following links.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] An informal classification of invertebrates between macroinvertebrates, which can be seen with the naked eye, and microinvertebrates which cannot be seen by the unaided eye is used for convenience.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] The line is arbitrarily drawn at a length of about 1 mm.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] The earliest animal fossils are of invertebrates.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] 665-million-year-old fossils in the Trezona Formation at Trezona Bore, West Central Flinders, South Australia have been interpreted as being early sponges.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Some paleontologists suggest that animals appeared much earlier, possibly as early as 1 billion years ago though they probably became multicellular in the Tonian.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Trace fossils such as tracks and burrows found in the late Neoproterozoic Era indicate the presence of triploblastic worms, roughly as large (about 5 mm wide) and complex as earthworms.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Around 453 MYA, animals began diversifying, and many of the important groups of invertebrates diverged from one another.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Fossils of invertebrates are found in various types of sediment from the Phanerozoic.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Fossils of invertebrates are commonly used in stratigraphy.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Carl Linnaeus divided these animals into only two groups, the Insecta and the now-obsolete Vermes (worms).
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] They are now classified into over 30 phyla, from simple organisms such as sea sponges and flatworms to complex animals such as arthropods and molluscs.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Invertebrates are animals without a vertebral column.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] This has led to the conclusion that *in*vertebrates are a group that deviates from the normal, vertebrates.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] It is also possible that some humans believe that, they themselves being vertebrates, the group deserves more attention than invertebrates.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] In addition, some species included are only remotely related to one another, with some more related to vertebrates than other invertebrates (see Paraphyly).
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] For many centuries, invertebrates were neglected by biologists, in favor of big vertebrates and "useful" or charismatic species.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Invertebrate biology was not a major field of study until the work of Linnaeus and Lamarck in the 18th century.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] During the 20th century, invertebrate zoology became one of the major fields of natural sciences, with prominent discoveries in the fields of medicine, genetics, palaeontology, and ecology.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] The study of invertebrates has also benefited law enforcement, as arthropods, and especially insects, were discovered to be a source of information for forensic investigators.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Two of the most commonly studied model organisms nowadays are invertebrates: the fruit fly *Drosophila melanogaster* and the nematode *Caenorhabditis elegans*.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] They have long been the most intensively studied model organisms, and were among the first life-forms to be genetically sequenced.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] This was facilitated by the severely reduced state of their genomes, but many genes, introns, and linkages have been lost.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Analysis of the starlet sea anemone genome has emphasised the importance of sponges, placozoans, and choanoflagellates, also being sequenced, in explaining the arrival of 1,500 ancestral genes unique to animals.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/invertebrate] Invertebrates are also used by scientists in the field of aquatic biomonitoring to evaluate the effects of water pollution and climate change.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] A **microorganism**, or **microbe**, is an organism of microscopic size, which may exist in its single-celled form or as a colony of cells.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] The possible existence of unseen microbial life was suspected from antiquity, with an early attestation in Jain literature authored in 6th-century BC India.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] The scientific study of microorganisms began with their observation under the microscope in the 1670s by Anton van Leeuwenhoek.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] In the 1850s, Louis Pasteur found that microorganisms caused food spoilage, debunking the theory of spontaneous generation.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] In the 1880s, Robert Koch discovered that microorganisms caused the diseases tuberculosis, cholera, diphtheria, and anthrax.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Microorganisms are extremely diverse, representing most unicellular organisms in all three domains of life: two of the three domains, Archaea and Bacteria, only contain microorganisms.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] The third domain, Eukaryota, includes all multicellular organisms as well as many unicellular protists and protozoans that are microbes.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Some protists are related to animals and some to green plants.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Many multicellular organisms are also microscopic, namely micro-animals, some fungi, and some algae.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Microorganisms can have very different habitats, and live everywhere from the poles to the equator, in deserts, geysers, rocks, and the deep sea.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Some are adapted to extremes such as very hot or very cold conditions, others to high pressure, and a few, such as *Deinococcus radiodurans*, to high radiation environments.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Microbes are a vital component of fertile soil.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Microorganisms also make up the microbiota found in and on all multicellular organisms.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] There is evidence that 3.45-billion-year-old Australian rocks once contained microorganisms, the earliest direct evidence of life on Earth.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Microbes are important in human culture and health in many ways, serving to ferment foods and treat sewage, and to produce fuel, enzymes, and other compounds.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Microbes are essential tools in biology as model organisms and have been put to use in biological warfare and bioterrorism.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] In the human body, microorganisms make up the human microbiota, including the essential gut flora.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] The pathogens responsible for many infectious diseases are microbes and, as such, are the target of hygiene measures.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] The possible existence of microscopic organisms was discussed for many centuries before their discovery in the 17th century.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] By the 6th century BC, the Jains of present-day India postulated the existence of tiny organisms called *nigodas*.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] These nigodas are said to be born in clusters; they live everywhere, including the bodies of plants, animals, and people; and their life lasts only for a fraction of a second.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] According to Mahavira, the 24th preacher of Jainism, the humans destroy these nigodas on a massive scale, when they eat, breathe, sit, and move.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Many modern Jains assert that Mahavira's teachings presage the existence of microorganisms as discovered by science.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] In *The Canon of Medicine* (1020), Avicenna suggested that tuberculosis and other diseases might be contagious.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] In 1546, Girolamo Fracastoro proposed that epidemic diseases were caused by transferable seedlike entities that could transmit infection by direct or indirect contact, or even without contact over long distances.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Antonie van Leeuwenhoek is considered one of the fathers of microbiology.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] He was the first in 1673 to discover and conduct scientific experiments with microorganisms, using simple single-lensed microscopes of his own design.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Robert Hooke, a contemporary of Leeuwenhoek, also used microscopy to observe microbial life in the form of the fruiting bodies of moulds.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] In his 1665 book *Micrographia*, he made drawings of studies, and he coined the term *cell*.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] By boiling the broth beforehand, Pasteur ensured that no microorganisms survived within the broths at the beginning of his experiment.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Nothing grew in the broths in the course of Pasteur's experiment.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] This meant that the living organisms that grew in such broths came from outside, as spores on dust, rather than spontaneously generated within the broth.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Thus, Pasteur refuted the theory of spontaneous generation and supported the germ theory of disease.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] In 1876, Robert Koch (1843–1910) established that microorganisms can cause disease.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] He found that the blood of cattle that were infected with anthrax always had large numbers of *Bacillus anthracis*.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Koch found that he could transmit anthrax from one animal to another by taking a small sample of blood from the infected animal and injecting it into a healthy one, and this caused the healthy animal to become sick.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] He also found that he could grow the bacteria in a nutrient broth, then inject it into a healthy animal, and cause illness.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Based on these experiments, he devised criteria for establishing a causal link between a microorganism and a disease and these are now known as Koch's postulates.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Although these postulates cannot be applied in all cases, they do retain historical importance to the development of scientific thought and are still being used today.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] The discovery of microorganisms such as *Euglena* that did not fit into either the animal or plant kingdoms, since they were photosynthetic like plants, but motile like animals, led to the naming of a third kingdom in the 1860s.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] In 1860 John Hogg called this the Protoctista, and in 1866 Ernst Haeckel named it the Protista.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] The work of Pasteur and Koch did not accurately reflect the true diversity of the microbial world because of their exclusive focus on microorganisms having direct medical relevance.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] It was not until the work of Martinus Beijerinck and Sergei Winogradsky in the late 19th century that the true breadth of microbiology was revealed.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Beijerinck made two major contributions to microbiology: the discovery of viruses and the development of enrichment culture techniques.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] While his work on the tobacco mosaic virus established the basic principles of virology, it was his development of enrichment culturing that had the most immediate impact on microbiology by allowing for the cultivation of a wide range of microbes with wildly different physiologies.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Winogradsky was the first to develop the concept of chemolithotrophy and to thereby reveal the essential role played by microorganisms in geochemical processes.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] He was responsible for the first isolation and description of both nitrifying and nitrogen-fixing bacteria.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] French-Canadian microbiologist Félix d'Hérelle co-discovered bacteriophages and was one of the earliest applied microbiologists.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Microorganisms can be found almost anywhere on Earth.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Bacteria and archaea are almost always microscopic, while a number of eukaryotes are also microscopic, including most protists, some fungi, as well as some micro-animals and plants.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Viruses are generally regarded as not living and therefore not considered to be microorganisms, although a subfield of microbiology is virology, the study of viruses.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Single-celled microorganisms were the first forms of life to develop on Earth, approximately 3.5 billion years ago.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Further evolution was slow, and for about 3 billion years in the Precambrian eon, (much of the history of life on Earth), all organisms were microorganisms.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Bacteria, algae and fungi have been identified in amber that is 220 million years old, which shows that the morphology of microorganisms has changed little since at least the Triassic period.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] The newly discovered biological role played by nickel, however – especially that brought about by volcanic eruptions from the Siberian Traps – may have accelerated the evolution of methanogens towards the end of the Permian–Triassic extinction event.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Microorganisms tend to have a relatively fast rate of evolution.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Most microorganisms can reproduce rapidly, and bacteria are also able to freely exchange genes through conjugation, transformation and transduction, even between widely divergent species.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] This horizontal gene transfer, coupled with a high mutation rate and other means of transformation, allows microorganisms to swiftly evolve (via natural selection) to survive in new environments and respond to environmental stresses.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] This rapid evolution is important in medicine, as it has led to the development of multidrug resistant pathogenic bacteria, *superbugs*, that are resistant to antibiotics.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] A possible transitional form of microorganism between a prokaryote and a eukaryote was discovered in 2012 by Japanese scientists.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] *Parakaryon myojinensis* is a unique microorganism larger than a typical prokaryote, but with nuclear material enclosed in a membrane as in a eukaryote, and the presence of endosymbionts.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] This is seen to be the first plausible evolutionary form of microorganism, showing a stage of development from the prokaryote to the eukaryote.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Archaea are prokaryotic unicellular organisms, and form the first domain of life in Carl Woese's three-domain system.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] A prokaryote is defined as having no cell nucleus or other membrane bound-organelle.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Archaea share this defining feature with the bacteria with which they were once grouped.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] In 1990 the microbiologist Woese proposed the three-domain system that divided living things into bacteria, archaea and eukaryotes, and thereby split the prokaryote domain.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Archaea differ from bacteria in both their genetics and biochemistry.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] For example, while bacterial cell membranes are made from phosphoglycerides with ester bonds, Achaean membranes are made of ether lipids.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Archaea were originally described as extremophiles living in extreme environments, such as hot springs, but have since been found in all types of habitats.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Only now are scientists beginning to realize how common archaea are in the environment, with Thermoproteota (formerly Crenarchaeota) being the most common form of life in the ocean, dominating ecosystems below 150 metres (490 ft) in depth.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] These organisms are also common in soil and play a vital role in ammonia oxidation.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] The combined domains of archaea and bacteria make up the most diverse and abundant group of organisms on Earth and inhabit practically all environments where the temperature is below +140 °C (284 °F).
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] They are found in water, soil, air, as the microbiome of an organism, hot springs and even deep beneath the Earth's crust in rocks.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] The number of prokaryotes is estimated to be around five nonillion, or 5 × 1030, accounting for at least half the biomass on Earth.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] The biodiversity of the prokaryotes is unknown, but may be very large.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] A May 2016 estimate, based on laws of scaling from known numbers of species against the size of organism, gives an estimate of perhaps 1 trillion species on the planet, of which most would be microorganisms.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Currently, only one-thousandth of one percent of that total have been described.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Archael cells of some species aggregate and transfer DNA from one cell to another through direct contact, particularly under stressful environmental conditions that cause DNA damage.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Like archaea, bacteria are prokaryotic – unicellular, and having no cell nucleus or other membrane-bound organelle.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Bacteria are microscopic, with a few extremely rare exceptions, such as *Thiomargarita namibiensis*.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Bacteria function and reproduce as individual cells, but they can often aggregate in multicellular colonies.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Some species such as myxobacteria can aggregate into complex swarming structures, operating as multicellular groups as part of their life cycle, or form clusters in bacterial colonies such as *E. coli*.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Their genome is usually a circular bacterial chromosome – a single loop of DNA, although they can also harbor small pieces of DNA called plasmids.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] These plasmids can be transferred between cells through bacterial conjugation.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Bacteria have an enclosing cell wall, which provides strength and rigidity to their cells.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] They reproduce by binary fission or sometimes by budding, but do not undergo meiotic sexual reproduction.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] However, many bacterial species can transfer DNA between individual cells by a horizontal gene transfer process referred to as natural transformation.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Some species form extraordinarily resilient spores, but for bacteria this is a mechanism for survival, not reproduction.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Under optimal conditions bacteria can grow extremely rapidly and their numbers can double as quickly as every 20 minutes.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Most living things that are visible to the naked eye in their adult form are eukaryotes, including humans.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] However, many eukaryotes are also microorganisms.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Unlike bacteria and archaea, eukaryotes contain organelles such as the cell nucleus, the Golgi apparatus and mitochondria in their cells.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] The nucleus is an organelle that houses the DNA that makes up a cell's genome.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] DNA (Deoxyribonucleic acid) itself is arranged in complex chromosomes.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Mitochondria are organelles vital in metabolism as they are the site of the citric acid cycle and oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] They evolved from symbiotic bacteria and retain a remnant genome.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Like bacteria, plant cells have cell walls, and contain organelles such as chloroplasts in addition to the organelles in other eukaryotes.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Chloroplasts produce energy from light by photosynthesis, and were also originally symbiotic bacteria.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Unicellular eukaryotes consist of a single cell throughout their life cycle.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] This qualification is significant since most multicellular eukaryotes consist of a single cell called a zygote only at the beginning of their life cycles.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Microbial eukaryotes can be either haploid or diploid, and some organisms have multiple cell nuclei.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Unicellular eukaryotes usually reproduce asexually by mitosis under favorable conditions.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] However, under stressful conditions such as nutrient limitations and other conditions associated with DNA damage, they tend to reproduce sexually by meiosis and syngamy.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Of eukaryotic groups, the protists are most commonly unicellular and microscopic.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] This is a highly diverse group of organisms that are not easy to classify.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Several algae species are multicellular protists, and slime molds have unique life cycles that involve switching between unicellular, colonial, and multicellular forms.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] The number of species of protists is unknown since only a small proportion has been identified.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Protist diversity is high in oceans, deep sea-vents, river sediment and an acidic river, suggesting that many eukaryotic microbial communities may yet be discovered.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] The fungi have several unicellular species, such as baker's yeast (*Saccharomyces cerevisiae*) and fission yeast (*Schizosaccharomyces pombe*).
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Some fungi, such as the pathogenic yeast *Candida albicans*, can undergo phenotypic switching and grow as single cells in some environments, and filamentous hyphae in others.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] The green algae are a large group of photosynthetic eukaryotes that include many microscopic organisms.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Although some green algae are classified as protists, others such as charophyta are classified with embryophyte plants, which are the most familiar group of land plants.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Algae can grow as single cells, or in long chains of cells.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] The green algae include unicellular and colonial flagellates, usually but not always with two flagella per cell, as well as various colonial, coccoid, and filamentous forms.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] In the Charales, which are the algae most closely related to higher plants, cells differentiate into several distinct tissues within the organism.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] There are about 6000 species of green algae.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Microorganisms are found in almost every habitat present in nature, including hostile environments such as the North and South poles, deserts, geysers, and rocks.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] They also include all the marine microorganisms of the oceans and deep sea.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Some types of microorganisms have adapted to extreme environments and sustained colonies; these organisms are known as extremophiles.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Extremophiles have been isolated from rocks as much as 7 kilometres below the Earth's surface, and it has been suggested that the amount of organisms living below the Earth's surface is comparable with the amount of life on or above the surface.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Extremophiles have been known to survive for a prolonged time in a vacuum, and can be highly resistant to radiation, which may even allow them to survive in space.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Many types of microorganisms have intimate symbiotic relationships with other larger organisms; some of which are mutually beneficial (mutualism), while others can be damaging to the host organism (parasitism).
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] If microorganisms can cause disease in a host they are known as *pathogens*.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Microorganisms play critical roles in Earth's biogeochemical cycles as they are responsible for decomposition and nitrogen fixation.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Bacteria use regulatory networks that allow them to adapt to almost every environmental niche on earth.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] A network of interactions among diverse types of molecules including DNA, RNA, proteins and metabolites, is utilised by the bacteria to achieve regulation of gene expression.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] In bacteria, the principal function of regulatory networks is to control the response to environmental changes, for example nutritional status and environmental stress.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] A complex organization of networks permits the microorganism to coordinate and integrate multiple environmental signals.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Extremophiles are microorganisms that have adapted so that they can survive and even thrive in extreme environments that are normally fatal to most life-forms.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Thermophiles and hyperthermophiles thrive in high temperatures.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Psychrophiles thrive in extremely low temperatures. – Temperatures as high as 130 °C (266 °F), as low as −17 °C (1 °F) Halophiles such as *Halobacterium salinarum* (an archaean) thrive in high salt conditions, up to saturation.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Alkaliphiles thrive in an alkaline pH of about 8.5–11.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Acidophiles can thrive in a pH of 2.0 or less.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Piezophiles thrive at very high pressures: up to 1,000–2,000 atm, down to 0 atm as in a vacuum of space.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] A few extremophiles such as *Deinococcus radiodurans* are radioresistant, resisting radiation exposure of up to 5k Gy.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Extremophiles are significant in different ways.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] The nitrogen cycle in soils depends on the fixation of atmospheric nitrogen.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] This is achieved by a number of diazotrophs.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] One way this can occur is in the root nodules of legumes that contain symbiotic bacteria of the genera *Rhizobium*, *Mesorhizobium*, *Sinorhizobium*, *Bradyrhizobium*, and *Azorhizobium*.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] The roots of plants create a narrow region known as the rhizosphere that supports many microorganisms known as the root microbiome.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] These microorganisms in the root microbiome are able to interact with each other and surrounding plants through signals and cues.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] For example, mycorrhizal fungi are able to communicate with the root systems of many plants through chemical signals between both the plant and fungi.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] This results in a mutualistic symbiosis between the two.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] However, these signals can be eavesdropped by other microorganisms, such as the soil bacteria, *Myxococcus xanthus*, which preys on other bacteria.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Eavesdropping, or the interception of signals from unintended receivers, such as plants and microorganisms, can lead to large-scale, evolutionary consequences.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] For example, signaler-receiver pairs, like plant-microorganism pairs, may lose the ability to communicate with neighboring populations because of variability in eavesdroppers.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] In adapting to avoid local eavesdroppers, signal divergence could occur and thus, lead to the isolation of plants and microorganisms from the inability to communicate with other populations.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] A lichen is a symbiosis of a macroscopic fungus with photosynthetic microbial algae or cyanobacteria.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Microorganisms are useful in producing foods, treating waste water, creating biofuels and a wide range of chemicals and enzymes.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] They are invaluable in research as model organisms.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] They have been weaponised and sometimes used in warfare and bioterrorism.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] They are vital to agriculture through their roles in maintaining soil fertility and in decomposing organic matter.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] They also have applications in aquaculture, such as in biofloc technology.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Microorganisms are used in a fermentation process to make yoghurt, cheese, curd, kefir, ayran, xynogala, and other types of food.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Fermentation cultures provide flavour and aroma, and inhibit undesirable organisms.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] They are used to leaven bread, and to convert sugars to alcohol in wine and beer.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Microorganisms are used in brewing, wine making, baking, pickling and other food-making processes.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] These depend for their ability to clean up water contaminated with organic material on microorganisms that can respire dissolved substances.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Respiration may be aerobic, with a well-oxygenated filter bed such as a slow sand filter.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Anaerobic digestion by methanogens generate useful methane gas as a by-product.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Microorganisms are used in fermentation to produce ethanol, and in biogas reactors to produce methane.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Scientists are researching the use of algae to produce liquid fuels, and bacteria to convert various forms of agricultural and urban waste into usable fuels.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Microorganisms are used to produce many commercial and industrial chemicals, enzymes and other bioactive molecules.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Microorganisms are used to prepare bioactive molecules such as Streptokinase from the bacterium *Streptococcus*, Cyclosporin A from the ascomycete fungus *Tolypocladium inflatum*, and statins produced by the yeast *Monascus purpureus*.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Microorganisms are essential tools in biotechnology, biochemistry, genetics, and molecular biology.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] The yeasts *Saccharomyces cerevisiae* and *Schizosaccharomyces pombe* are important model organisms in science, since they are simple eukaryotes that can be grown rapidly in large numbers and are easily manipulated.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] They are particularly valuable in genetics, genomics and proteomics.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Microorganisms can be harnessed for uses such as creating steroids and treating skin diseases.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Scientists are also considering using microorganisms for living fuel cells, and as a solution for pollution.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] In the Middle Ages, as an early example of biological warfare, diseased corpses were thrown into castles during sieges using catapults or other siege engines.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Individuals near the corpses were exposed to the pathogen and were likely to spread that pathogen to others.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] In modern times, bioterrorism has included the 1984 Rajneeshee bioterror attack and the 1993 release of anthrax by Aum Shinrikyo in Tokyo.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Microbes can make nutrients and minerals in the soil available to plants, produce hormones that spur growth, stimulate the plant immune system and trigger or dampen stress responses.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] In general a more diverse set of soil microbes results in fewer plant diseases and higher yield.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Microorganisms can form an endosymbiotic relationship with other, larger organisms.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] For example, microbial symbiosis plays a crucial role in the immune system.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] The microorganisms that make up the gut flora in the gastrointestinal tract contribute to gut immunity, synthesize vitamins such as folic acid and biotin, and ferment complex indigestible carbohydrates.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Some microorganisms that are seen to be beneficial to health are termed probiotics and are available as dietary supplements, or food additives.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Microorganisms are the causative agents (pathogens) in many infectious diseases.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] The organisms involved include pathogenic bacteria, causing diseases such as plague, tuberculosis and anthrax; protozoan parasites, causing diseases such as malaria, sleeping sickness, dysentery and toxoplasmosis; and also fungi causing diseases such as ringworm, candidiasis or histoplasmosis.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] However, other diseases such as influenza, yellow fever or AIDS are caused by pathogenic viruses, which are not usually classified as living organisms and are not, therefore, microorganisms by the strict definition.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] No clear examples of archaean pathogens are known, although a relationship has been proposed between the presence of some archaean methanogens and human periodontal disease.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Numerous microbial pathogens are capable of sexual processes that appear to facilitate their survival in their infected host.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Hygiene is a set of practices to avoid infection or food spoilage by eliminating microorganisms from the surroundings.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] As microorganisms, in particular bacteria, are found virtually everywhere, harmful microorganisms may be reduced to acceptable levels rather than actually eliminated.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] In food preparation, microorganisms are reduced by preservation methods such as cooking, cleanliness of utensils, short storage periods, or by low temperatures.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] If complete sterility is needed, as with surgical equipment, an autoclave is used to kill microorganisms with heat and pressure.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] Wells's 1898 science fiction novel *The War of the Worlds*, alien lifeforms attempt to conquer Earth and are ultimately defeated by a common microbe to which humans are immune.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] The 2001 film *Osmosis Jones* and its show *Ozzy & Drix* are set in a stylized version of the human body, featured anthropomorphic microorganisms.
[src:germplasm-resources-information-network/microbe] In the 2006 indie game *FlOw*, the player controls an aquatic microorganism that evolves by consuming other microorganisms.
